{
  "text": "Driving the system with an ancillary optical mode with a large damping rate (κ κ and κ γ i ) tuned to the red side of the optical cavity [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , as the consequence of the optomechanical interaction, the ancillary mode induces an optical damping to the mechanical oscillator. Working in the resolved-sideband regime and using a red detuned driving laser together with a small optomechanical single-photon coupling strength which guarantees neglecting the nonlinear optomechanical the net effect of the ancillary optical mode is to renormalize the mechanical damping rate according to Eq. (A11). In this manner, γ opt can be adjusted by the strength of the driving ancillary field so that the total damping rate of the mechanical oscillator, γ = γ opt + γ i becomes very large. Therefore, coupling a high-Q mechanical oscillator to an auxiliary cavity mode allows us to realize the RDR of the cavity optomechanics, γ κ [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] (see Figs. (1-b) and (1-c) ). The wide separation between the time scales of dissipation mechanisms allows us to use the mechanical oscillator as an extra dissipative reservoir for the optical mode.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "29864427",
